    <h2>
    Introduction to Chinook Salmon Fishing
</h2>
<p>
    Fishing for Chinook salmon near Portland, Oregon, isn't just a hobby — it's a deep-rooted tradition and a thrilling outdoor experience. Known as the “king” of salmon for their size and flavor, Chinook are a prized catch for locals and visitors alike. Nestled between mighty rivers and lush landscapes, Portland offers anglers diverse opportunities to reel in these majestic fish.
</p>
<h3>
    Why Chinook Salmon Are So Popular in Oregon
</h3>
<p>
    Chinook salmon are the largest species in the Pacific salmon family. They can weigh over 30 pounds and are famous for their rich, buttery taste. In Oregon, especially around Portland, they are more than just a fish — they represent cultural heritage, sport, and sustainability.
</p>
<h3>
    Key Characteristics of Chinook Salmon
</h3>
<p>
    Chinook salmon are recognized by their blue-green back, silver sides, and black spots on their tails and backs. During the spawning season, males develop hooked jaws and darken in color. These fish are powerful swimmers, making every catch a memorable fight.
</p>
<h2>
    Best Time of Year to Fish for Chinook Salmon
</h2>
<h3>
    Seasonal Migration Patterns
</h3>
<p>
    Chinook salmon migrate from the ocean to freshwater rivers to spawn. Near Portland, they usually begin appearing in rivers as early as March, with their numbers peaking at different times depending on the river system.
</p>
<h3>
    Peak Months Near Portland
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Spring Chinook (March–June)</strong>: Known for their incredible taste.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Fall Chinook (August–October)</strong>: Larger in size, with high catch rates.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Best Times</strong>: April-May for spring runs; September-October for fall runs.
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Top Fishing Spots Near Portland, Oregon
</h2>
<h3>
    Columbia River
</h3>
<p>
    The Columbia is a powerhouse for Chinook fishing. Anglers line up during spring and fall runs for a chance at trophy-sized salmon.
</p>
<h3>
    Willamette River
</h3>
<p>
    A tributary of the Columbia, the Willamette runs through downtown Portland and offers strong runs of spring Chinook.
</p>
<h3>
    Sandy River
</h3>
<p>
    Just east of Portland, this river is a favorite among local anglers for bank fishing opportunities.
</p>
<h3>
    Multnomah Channel
</h3>
<p>
    This narrow offshoot of the Willamette is a hotspot for early Chinook in the spring, especially near Sauvie Island.
</p>
<h2>
    Essential Gear for Chinook Salmon Fishing
</h2>
<h3>
    Rods and Reels
</h3>
<p>
    A medium-heavy rod (8-10 ft.) paired with a strong baitcasting reel and 30-50 lb test line is ideal.
</p>
<h3>
    Bait and Lures
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        Baits: Herring, salmon eggs, shrimp
    </li>
    <li>
        Lures: Spinners, wobblers, and plugs in chrome, red, or chartreuse colors
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    Waders, Nets, and Other Tools
</h3>
<p>
    Stay dry with chest waders, especially when fishing the banks. Long-handled landing nets help with large fish.
</p>
<h2>
    Techniques and Tips for Catching Chinook Salmon
</h2>
<h3>
    Drift Fishing vs. Trolling
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Drift Fishing</strong>: Ideal for rivers like the Sandy; use weights to keep bait near the bottom.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Trolling</strong>: Great on the Columbia; use flashers and plug-cut herring behind downriggers.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    Bank Fishing Strategies
</h3>
<p>
    Look for deeper holes and slower water near the banks. Float fishing and plunking work well here.
</p>
<h3>
    Boat Fishing Tips
</h3>
<p>
    Use sonar to locate schools. Anchor in high-traffic areas during peak times and rotate baits regularly.
</p>
